> Though again, my only question would be whether or not the stack trace was always included regardless of log level.

@BFergerson , I am not sure if there will be the following usage in a real environment:
```java
logger.debug("has exception",new Exception());
```
And the information just above needs to be recorded in the span log.

The format above appears to be more logback than log4j2. Also, I don't think there would be a need for a new line in the pattern as these logs are not going directly to the console.

I'm also having second thoughts about adding the file and line number to the pattern. I forgot these incur a [performance cost](https://logging.apache.org/log4j/2.x/manual/layouts.html#LocationInformation). I still would like to be able to correlate this information but again I'm not completely sure my needs represent what most people's needs are. Either way, I'm starting to think that an appropriate solution for me would be to simply store the log pattern and the parameters separately. Given that the logger plugin hooks into `trace/debug/info/error` method calls, it actually has access to both the pattern and the parameters. If I knew what the unformatted pattern was I can essentially do a grep to find the location (even using the logger name to limit the search even further).

There are some advantages to structured logs over unstructured logs. For example, given this log:
```java
log.warn("span {} has illegal status code {}", span, tag.getValue());
```

Storing this as unstructured would be saving the following map to a span:
```json
"logs": [
  {
    "time": 1605225365711,
    "data": [
      {
        "key": "event",
        "value": "warn"
      },
      {
        "key": "log.kind",
        "value": "org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.analyzer.provider.trace.parser.listener.MultiScopesAnalysisListener"
      },
      {
        "key": "message",
        "value": "span *span* has illegal status code *tag.getValue()*"
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

Now I'm unsure if SkyWalking plans on making the logs queryable but if I wanted to find all the logs where the `tag.getValue()` had a certain value, that would mean doing regex over the `message` variable. Alternatively, you could store both the pattern and the params, like so:
```json
"logs": [
  {
    "time": 1605225365711,
    "data": [
      {
        "key": "event",
        "value": "warn"
      },
      {
        "key": "log.kind",
        "value": "org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.analyzer.provider.trace.parser.listener.MultiScopesAnalysisListener"
      },
      {
        "key": "message",
        "value": "span {} has illegal status code {}"
      },
      {
        "key": "param.1",
        "value": "*span*"
      },
      {
        "key": "param.2",
        "value": "*tag.getValue()*"
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

I think storing logs this way could provide some benefits when it comes to making them queryable. It would also solve my desire to be able to correlate the source code location of the data being logged as now I can simply grep by the message. There could also be benefits to RocketBot/CLI visualization as the user could then reformat logs on the client-side as they see fit and the structure of the logs wouldn't need to be processed on-the-fly by the SkyWalking agent (so maybe that'll help with processing time).

Let me know what you guys think. As always, I'm fine simply creating a PR later on to add extra configuration to suit my needs.

> It looks like the `structure` proposal is better, less performance impact, still readable, and has more possibilities in the future. Personally like this. @vcjmhg thoughts?

@wu-sheng , yes, I also agree that `structured` proposal seems better, more flexible.

And I have a question that is support for the `pattern` field necessary.
